# Vitest Unit Testing

This project uses Vitest with jsdom, `@testing-library/react`, and `@testing-library/jest-dom` (see `vitest.config.mts` and `vitest.setup.ts`).

## Focus

- Test business logic (`src/lib/`) and component behavior (`src/components/`).
- Mock external dependencies (MongoDB, env, network) before imports when needed.
- Cover valid inputs, invalid inputs, and edge cases.

## Conventions

- Colocate tests as `*.test.ts` or `*.test.tsx` next to the module under test.
- Use `describe` blocks grouped by function or component; use clear `it` names.
- Import from `vitest`: `describe`, `it`, `expect`, `vi`, `beforeEach`.
- For React components: `render`, `screen` from `@testing-library/react`.

## Mocking

```ts
import { vi } from "vitest";

vi.mock("@/lib/mongodb", () => ({
  getDb: vi.fn(),
}));
```

- Call `vi.clearAllMocks()` in `beforeEach` when mocks are shared across tests.
- Prefer mocking at module boundaries (`getDb`, env helpers) over internal implementation details.

## Component tests

- Query by role, label, or accessible name (`getByRole`, `getByText`).
- Build realistic fixtures (see `MovieCard.test.tsx` for `Movie` shape).
- Assert user-visible output, not CSS class names or internal state.

## Lib tests

- Test pure functions without I/O (see `movies.test.ts`, `regex.test.ts`).
- Keep tests fast and deterministic — no live MongoDB in unit tests.

## Quantity

- Aim for 3–5 focused tests per file covering the critical paths.
- Add tests when fixing bugs or adding non-trivial logic.
